SIMPLE: mix
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mix
<hw>Mix</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧ks)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mixed</conjf> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧kst)</pr> (less properly
<conjf>Mixt</conjf>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mixing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>miscan</ets>; akin to
OHG. <ets>misken</ets>, G. <ets>mischen</ets>, Russ.
<ets>mieshate</ets>, W. <ets>mysgu</ets>, Gael. <ets>measg</ets>, L.
<ets>miscere</ets>, <ets>mixtum</ets>, Gr. <grk>mi`sgein</grk>,
<grk>migny`nai</grk>, Skr. <ets>mi⟦cced⟧ra</ets> mixed. The English word
has been influenced by L. <ets>miscere</ets>, <ets>mixtum</ets> (cf.
<er>Mixture</er>), and even the AS. <ets>miscan</ets> may have been
borrowed fr. L. <ets>miscere</ets>. Cf. <er>Admix</er>, <er>Mash</er> to
bruise, <er>Meddle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause a promiscuous
interpenetration of the parts of, as of two or more substances with each
other, or of one substance with others; to unite or blend into one mass
or compound, as by stirring together; to mingle; to blend; <as>as, to
<ex>mix</ex> flour and salt; to <ex>mix</ex> wines.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fair persuasions <qex>mixed</qex> with sugared words.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To unite with in company; to join; to
associate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ephraim, he hath <qex>mixed</qex> himself among the people.</q>
<rj><qau>Hos. vii. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To form by mingling; to produce by the stirring
together of ingredients; to compound of different parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hast thou no poison <qex>mixed</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have chosen an argument <qex>mixed</qex> of religious and civil
considerations.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To combine (two or more activities) within a
specified or implied time frame; <as>as, to <ex>mix</ex> studying and
partying while at college</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mix</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mix
<hw>Mix</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become
united into a compound; to be blended promiscuously together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To associate; to mingle; <as>as, Democrats and
Republicans <ex>mixed</ex> freely at the party</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had <qex>mixed</qex>⟦br⟧
Again in fancied safety with his kind.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixable</ent>⟦br⟧
